Task Content:
It was identified during QA phase that the name matching for certain features that is handled by RAAS middleware, did not work the same way than other features where the name matching is handled by the Numi Platform.
It is necessary to enhace the name matching used in RAAS middleware to achieve the same logic than the Platform one
@Claudia and @Ricardo will work to have this feature in RAAS working the same as in the Platform

There is a mechanism in the platform (a service) that allows under certain circunstances to re-activate a Transaction that was set on Hold due to some reason (e.g the payment method was failed or the provider sent an error)

This mechanism was not available to be used

It is necessary to provide the access to this mechanism in the console

{panel:bgColor=#eae6ff}
The transactions adopt the retry mechanism in the steps of the flow where a failure can be occur (commonly in provider integration). 

At the moment, the configuration key RetriesTimesInMinutes sets two retries every 2 minutes when a step failed.

Therefore, the reactivation is possible when the transaction is OnHold / WaitingRetryStep and after three retries. Then, the console shows the buttons to continue o cancel transaction if the user is authorized.
{panel}



{panel:bgColor=#eae6ff}
{color:#403294}Note From TA: {color}
{color:#403294}The “continue operation” feature in the console, will be provided to allow the operations team to continue an operation that has been set on hold due to have finished the retries mechanism after a system/networking/provider failure.{color}

{color:#403294}This mechanism is provided to help continue an operation if the  system/networking/provider failure that caused the retries in the first place, was fixed, and with the “back to normal” situation the operation may be executed successfully.{color}

{color:#403294}The retries will be re-started and the operation will continue in the same moment of the lifecycle it was hold {color}
{panel}

{color:#4c9aff}Please review the story links for business and UX considerations{color}

{color:#172b4d}The following story describes the moments when the user will visualize warnings before getting his account blocked (e.g. inaccessible to log-in or further use), and the situations where the account will get effectively blocked.{color}

{color:#172b4d}Scenario 1:{color}
 {color:#172b4d}When the user enter his credentials wrongly, he will get two more attempts. {color}
 {color:#172b4d}In the first two attempts the application will display an {color}{color:#172b4d}inline message{color}{color:#172b4d} with a warning, describing the number of wrong attempts (1 or 2) and the total of failed attempts that will get the account blocked .{color}
 {color:#172b4d}By the third attempt the account will be blocked.{color}
 {color:#172b4d}After this occurs, when logging in, the user will get an error message stating that his account is blocked, due to many failed login attempts, and he needs to call Customer Support to get it un-blocked.{color}
{color:#172b4d}Scenario 2:{color}
 {color:#172b4d}When the user does not use the application for a long period of time, this is, a period of time where the user did not start a session into the application, he will get his account blocked.{color}
 {color:#172b4d}The period of "out of use" time may vary in the different implementations, depending on a configured value. {color}
 {color:#172b4d}When the use logs-in, if the time elapsed between that last active session and the current time, reaches the configured value, the user will have his account blocked, {color}
 Note: in this scenario theres no possibility to display a warning to the user, the account gets blocked directly
** After this occurs, when logging in, the user will get an error message stating that his account is blocked due to the long period of time out of use,  and that he needs to call Customer Support to get it un-blocked.
Scenario 3:
* {color:#6554c0} this scenario is blocked for dependency with other feature, so it needs to be reviewed as a separated feature in:*{color}  https://leapfinancial.atlassian.net/browse/SAC-1845 

 General Notes to All Scenarios

The account lock/unlock scenarios should be configured by country. This is, the rules to lock the user's account will be present, or not, according to the country available in the user's profile
In each case, when a full screen error/warning message is displayed, the user will not be available to perform any other action than accept the message
If the account is already blocked the user will only get an error message after an attempt to enter his credentials
If the account is about to be blocked, and the user gets a warning message, depending on the scenario, a successful login will reset the attempts count.
After the user accepts a full screen error/warning message,  the login screen will be displayed

(!) The only way the user will get his account back is by calling customer support. There will be a mechanism in customer support dashboard to unlock the user password and allow him to use an authentication factor to gain back his credentials.

{color:#ffc300} Still to be determined the means to emulate the User Account Unlock for Testing Purposes in SAC-602{color}

The mechanism for the user to unlock his account will be as follows

1) User will call Customer Support

2) Customer Support will establish the authentication factor "something you are" by asking a pre-formatted questionnaire to identify the user properly

3) Once the user is identified by the Customer Support Operator, he will proceed to send a personal authentication message to the user´s device and request the user to read such message

3) The user will read to the message to the Operator and by this mean validate completely two authentication factors (something you are/ something you have)

4) The Customer Support Operator will unblock the user´s account

5) The user will be able to access the application using his existing credentials
